Assignment 4: EICU-v2.0 database¶

Student name: Phan Hoang An Nguyen

Dataset name: eICU Collaborative Research Database v2.0

Dataset source: The eICU Collaborative Research Database, a freely available multi-center database for critical care research. Pollard TJ, Johnson AEW, Raffa JD, Celi LA, Mark RG and Badawi O. Scientific Data (2018). DOI: 10.1038/sdata.2018.178. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/sdata2018178

Objectives

We tried to re-create the findings from the article below by using machine learning to build predictive model to predict the status of partient in first admission to the ICU:

  • Peer review article as reference: Na Pattalung, T., Ingviya, T., & Chaichulee, S. (2021). Feature explanations in recurrent neural networks for predicting risk of mortality in intensive care patients. Journal of Personalized Medicine, 11(9), 934.
  • Below is the ERD of table that were used for query

  • Below is the workflow of SQL query step by step. Please refer to the txt file for SQL codes to extract data by Snowflake.

  • Usually by the rules of thumb, we can't impute values of columns that have missing values over 50% otherwise it'd affect the distribution of variables and introduce considerable bias so it's best to drop them

There are many missing values so data cleaning is required. Most of the missing values came from Vital signs and Lab tests features. Theoretically, there are 3 types of missing data, we need to understand which features above that have what type of missing data. If possible, it's better to have MCAR than the other 2.

  1. Missing Completely at Random (MCAR): The missingness has no relationship with any values, observed or unobserved.
  2. Missing at Random (MAR): The missingness is related to some of the observed data but not the missing data itself.
  3. Missing Not at Random (MNAR): The missingness is related to the value of the missing data itself.

Missing data imputation¶

  • BILIRUBIN and ALBUMIN missing values are strongly correlated as well but they only miss ~20% so I can use IterativeImputer to handle the imputation of multiple columns with missing values by iteratively using regression models in this case because imputation by linear regression cannot compute when both columns have missing data
In [ ]:
# Impute missing values in 'BILIRUBIN', 'ALBUMIN' columns by IterativeImputer
from sklearn.experimental import enable_iterative_imputer
from sklearn.impute import IterativeImputer

columns_to_impute = ['BILIRUBIN', 'ALBUMIN']

# Initialize IterativeImputer
imputer = IterativeImputer(max_iter=10, random_state=0)

# Fit and transform the data
eicu_imputed = pd.DataFrame(imputer.fit_transform(eicu_clean[columns_to_impute]), columns=columns_to_impute)

# Replace the original columns with the imputed values
eicu_clean[columns_to_impute] = eicu_imputed

# Check missing values
print('Number of missing data in BILIRUBIN: ', eicu_clean['BILIRUBIN'].isnull().sum())
print('Number of missing data in ALBUMIN: ', eicu_clean['ALBUMIN'].isnull().sum())

Number of missing data in BILIRUBIN:  939
Number of missing data in ALBUMIN:  939
  • UNITDISCHARGESTATUS is our target feature and it has 0.8% missing data. It's best to drop those rows instead of imputing

LDA (Linear Discriminant Analysis) as Feature Reduction¶

  • LDA transforms the original features into a new lower-dimensional space. The new features are linear combinations of the original features, and these combinations are chosen to maximize class separability while projecting the data onto a subspace with fewer dimensions (components), where the separation between different classes is maximized. The new dimensions are created based on the data's class information
In [ ]:
from sklearn.discriminant_analysis import LinearDiscriminantAnalysis as LDA
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_score
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from imblearn.under_sampling import RandomUnderSampler
In [ ]:
# Determine the best number of components
max_components = min(len(X.columns), len(set(y)) - 1)
best_score = 0
best_n_components = 0

for n in range(1, max_components + 1):
    lda = LDA(n_components=n)
    scores = cross_val_score(lda, X_scaled, y, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
    mean_score = scores.mean()
    print(f"n_components = {n}, Accuracy = {mean_score}")

    if mean_score > best_score:
        best_score = mean_score
        best_n_components = n

print(f"Best n_components = {best_n_components}, Best Accuracy = {best_score}")

n_components = 1, Accuracy = 0.9244886054599126
Best n_components = 1, Best Accuracy = 0.9244886054599126
In [ ]:
# Transform data by LDA based on CV best result above
lda = LDA(n_components=1)
X_lda = lda.fit_transform(X_scaled, y)

SelectKBest as Feature Selection technique¶

  • Feature selection method in the sklearn library that selects the top k features based on univariate statistical tests. It helps in reducing the dimensionality of the dataset by selecting the most relevant features. The method works by scoring each feature using a specific scoring function and then selecting the features with the highest scores.
  • Scoring: Each feature is scored individually based on its relationship with the target variable. Various scoring functions can be used, depending on the nature of the data
  • Here we use f_classif = ANOVA F-value between label/feature for classification tasks
In [ ]:
# Standardize
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Undersample the data using NearMiss-3
nearmiss = NearMiss(version=3)
X_res, y_res = nearmiss.fit_resample(X_scaled, y)

Selected features: Index(['BLOOD_UREA_NITROGEN', 'CREATININE'], dtype='object')
In [ ]:
# Determine which k value is the best
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest, f_classif

max_features = X.shape[1]
accuracies = []
range_k = [1,5,10,15,20,24]

for k in range_k:
    selector = SelectKBest(score_func=f_classif, k=k)
    X_selected = selector.fit_transform(X_res, y_res)
    rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
    scores = cross_val_score(rf, X_selected, y_res, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
    mean_score = scores.mean()
    accuracies.append(mean_score)
    print(f"k = {k}, Accuracy = {mean_score}")
